##The unseaworthy diamond princess

Wechat, renwumag1980

Feature Introduction, the best Chinese character report

By the ninth day of the ship's offshore quarantine, 174 people had been confirmed with new crown pneumonia, more than the total number of confirmed cases in Japan and rising. A new virus has suddenly arrived, a quarantine has suddenly arrived, a ship that can not be docked. The "Diamond Princess" is a metaphor for the fragility of the seemingly smooth-running modern social system.

By Lai Yuxuan

Editor | locust tree

Cover | Reuters

Can't make it to shore

The boat was about to dock, Takahashi thought. After getting off the ship to eat mcdonald's, roast meat and beef covered rice. He has been at sea for 12 days since boarding the diamond princess in Yokohama on January 20,2020. It was February 1, from Kagoshima, Kyushu, through Hong Kong, Da Nang, Port of Keelung, Okinawa, Japan. Two days later, he would arrive in Port of Yokohama, where he had started. Born more than 30 years ago, he took his first trip on a luxury cruise, or, more accurately, his first time on a cruise. He was so excited that he got off the boat at every scenic spot and took part in local sightseeing activities. On Feb. 1, he and his fellow passengers spent a day sightseeing in the island's capital, Naha, when the ship docked. Little did he know that this was the last time he would be off the ship for the next month. He had a good time, although most of his fellow passengers were elderly people who seemed to have retired.

Late that night, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare announced that an 80 year old Hong Kong passenger on board the ship had been diagnosed with COVID-19, and that he had disembarked seven days earlier, but that the people on board were at risk.

At 8 p.m. on Feb. 3, the diamond princess arrived in Port of Yokohama 10 hours ahead of schedule, two days after her full sail. The 3711 were supposed to disembark, but Takahashi, and everyone on board, heard the announcement: The ship can not dock, and everyone must remain on the ship for Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare quarantine. More than 200 people in close contact with infected people in Hong Kong will be quarantined first.

Takahashi immediately tweeted that the "Diamond Princess" cruise ship was about to be quarantined, and next to his name, he tagged it "On board the Diamond Princess. ". Over the next week, he posted more than 1,500 tweets, becoming one of the most active providers of information about the ship on social media.

Made in Japan, the diamond princess is one of the largest passenger liners in the famous Princess Cruise Line of the Carnival Cruise Lines group. The voyage carried 2,666 passengers and 1,045 crew members, nearly half of whom were from Japan, followed by the United States and Canada. According to the Chinese Embassy in Japan, there were 287 Chinese passengers on board, including two from the mainland, 260 from Hong Kong, 20 from Taiwan and five from Macau, as well as 20 Chinese crew members.

The ship can't come ashore. Even as news of the Hong Kong man's infection spread around the world, cruise passengers continued to relax, believing the new virus had nothing to do with them. On the afternoon of the 3rd, at the end of the voyage, Takahashi saw people playing games in the lobby, playing cards and Mah Jongg in the poolside lounge, sitting around in the restaurant's warm yellow light, no less than the 8 p.m. show, people still came to the scene. Hardly anyone wears a mask.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Diamond Princess cruise ship Image Source Daxa

At 11:00 p.m. , the captain announced that all passengers must remain in their rooms and the quarantine officer must board. The atmosphere of leisure is gone. The next day, tests came back, and there were 10 confirmed cases on board. Once again, from February 5th, the 14-day quarantine has officially begun.

7 X 24 hours

At first, the feeling wasn't too bad, just a bit idle.

The "Diamond Princess" cruise ship has seven types of rooms, the big has 40 m2-80 M2, with independent balconies, the small only 14 M2. There is no balcony, only a small window, you can see the sea outside. The cabin is smaller, with no balconies or windows, but it has to accommodate three or four passengers. Takahashi lives in the smallest room in the inner cabin and spends his days tweeting and tweeting. In the confined space, 24 hours stretched indefinitely, he couldn't sleep at night and often thought he heard coughing on the deck or in the next room.

The Three Meals a Day is the only time passengers can communicate. Every day, the crew would knock on the door and deliver a menu, from appetizers to staples to desserts, that had hardly been repeated in a week. Passengers can order dishes, Japanese, western, Chinese cuisine can be almost satisfied. At dinnertime, the crew knocks again, serving a balanced menu of meat and vegetables, fruit and drinks. Passengers can take the opportunity to open the door and say "thank you" to the crew.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Food in the cabin source: DAXA

But that's it. Cruise ships prohibit more contact and communication between crew and passengers. As of February 5th, the ship's recreational facilities, swimming pools, casinos, spas, cinemas, cabarets, massages, are closed, and passengers are confined to their rooms for all time-consuming activities.

To help the passengers kill time, the cruise ship also came up with a lot of ways. After the quarantine, the network began to offer free, sometimes fast and sometimes slow. Eight TV channels, 60 movies, 24 hours a day, but most of them are in English with subtitles, and most of the passengers are from non English speaking countries. Some middle-aged women choose to watch the video of Taijiquan on TV. Every day, cruise passengers are also given colorful origami and Sudoku cards, two games that Japanese passengers prefer, with some posting complaints on social media for delivering only Sudoku and leaving the Origami behind one day.

SUDOKU cards sent by cruise ship to passengers

The isolation still seems too long.

Davy Niels Henrik Abel, 74, from the UK, is on a boat trip to celebrate his 50th anniversary with his wife. He broadcasts live on Facebook a few times a day about the ship's isolation. In the television report, he found that a British passenger had been diagnosed with a new coronary pneumonia, and he had dined at the same table as the confirmed passenger. Naturally, he was a little worried, but on live television, he said courteously that the confirmed passenger was on his honeymoon with his new wife. "I think she must be very upset. He also showed his room, a suite with an ocean view balcony. In addition to live streaming, all he can do is create from his balcony, holding up his camera and snapping pictures of Seagulls, shimmering sunsets and distant unreachable ports.

Chen Risheng, a magician from Taiwan, China, boarded the ship from Vietnam. He was happy when he was invited to his first cruise show in 2020. Then the quarantine began. He lived in a windowless room with no balcony and only a small view of the sea. He also went on the air and said it wasn't easy being on a boat. He also said that the virus will not be poor and lowly status, will be sick, will be sick.

More than boredom is on the rise, with some on social media saying, "this is a supermax. ". One of the world's most luxurious cruise ships has fallen silent for 24 hours. As Takahashi sees it, most of the passengers on board are elderly people, many of whom do not use smartphones. They didn't know much about the outside world at the time of the quarantine. But on the television news, the number of confirmed cases on the ship is increasing by the day. 10,41,65... Adrift, unable to Reach Land, panic and anxiety built up over time.

Takahashi still tweets every day. He said the captain had been broadcasting more frequently, eight times on the first day of the quarantine and, more recently, more than a dozen times a day. "More than the panic that the infected are sending out, it's the chaos of being in the house forever. He agreed to be interviewed by people, but it took him three days to respond to questions sent by the reporter. In the small, airless room, he slept, ate, tweeted, and waited for the inspection officers from shore to inspect the passengers in droves.

Passengers like Takahashi, who live in the inner cabin, are allowed on deck for an hour a day to breathe. During that hour, Takahashi would meet other passengers, but no one would talk to anyone. They kept a prudent distance. "The only thing they wanted to do was to breathe in the air while walking. "He told people.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A broken system

Others face problems far worse than Takahashi's.

We're out of medicine. You know, most of the passengers are old people. Many had underlying illnesses, but they had only the medicines on hand until February 4th, when they were expected to disembark. The sudden announcement of the quarantine disrupted everyone's plans and patients with diabetes, high blood pressure and cataracts began to suffer from physical problems caused by drug withdrawal. By February 9, more than 100 passengers had indicated that they were not feeling well, due to a disease unrelated to the new coronary pneumonia. Some were rushed to the hospital.

Of the 2,666 passengers aboard the Diamond Princess, 2,144 are over 60, accounting for 80 percent of the total, the Yomiuri reported. Takahashi also told people that many older people, especially in Japan, don't use the simplest flip phones, let alone smartphones that can access external information. Japanese passengers and their families have pinned their hopes on the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, which has repeatedly called the Ministry of Health and Welfare, and the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, which has released drug application forms that, according to public accounts, give passengers the information they need to get the drugs. But it doesn't happen that fast. Even after filling out drug applications, only 500 people received emergency drugs after five days of isolation. Anger is on the rise. On Feb. 9, a twitter search for the word "Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare" was followed by the first word "incompetent, " followed by coronavirus.

The Chinese Embassy in Japan sent some medicine and received a thank-you letter from a passenger in Hong Kong, China. Other passengers from countries other than Japan are still struggling to find medicine. On twitter, there is a daily deluge of requests for medical help, mostly from the families of passengers, usually young people, seeking help for their parents, grandparents, uncles and aunts. Every day, Florida Girl Ashley Asks Internet users from around the world how they can help her parents get their medicine on the ship. She thought about turning to the United States government, wrote an email, but did not respond. "I haven't heard from my parents in hours, " she told people at 4 a.m. in Tokyo on Feb. 9. "maybe they are asleep. There's no more information on how to access the drug, so please let me know if you know anything. "

People are used to the smooth operation of modern social systems, but a sudden emergence of a new virus, a sudden arrival of isolation, exposed the vulnerability of the system. An elderly Japanese woman waves to people on the shore holding up a Japanese flag that reads "insufficient medication. ". The men on the shore wrote down "what medicine" on a blank sheet of paper and unfolded it to her. The distribution of goods and the needs of the people, at this moment back to the most primitive communication.

Passengers on a cruise ship carrying a Japanese flag marked "under-medicated" photograph: DAXA

For many elderly people, the captain's radio is the only way to get information. Takahashi syncs the captain's audio on twitter every day. According to the company's website, the ship has passengers from 56 countries and regions, while the captain's broadcast is in English and Japanese. Takahashi felt it was unfriendly to many of the passengers from non British parts of the ship, and he had asked for help on twitter to translate the broadcast into Chinese. Another Japanese male passenger said that every time he listened to the radio, he felt like he was taking an English toeic hearing test and was very nervous.

The tightness of space and the stagnation of information have pushed many passengers to the brink of collapse. On Feb. 11, a Japanese passenger submitted a handwritten letter to the Japanese government, citing the plight of the passengers on board: Sheets that had not been changed for a week, living conditions that needed improvement; the need for medical assistance; Insufficient Information; and a cruise desk that ignored passenger needs The elderly and those with a history of illness are not well cared for; it is hoped that the Japanese government will set up a passenger demand phone line. Foreign passengers are less restrained, with an American couple reporting in the US media: "DONALD TRUMP, help us! "

On that day, a member of the Japanese cabinet suggested that asymptomatic passengers should be allowed off the ship for humanitarian reasons. However, after a vote, the proposal was rejected. The days of isolation must go on.

The crew disinfects the cabin image source DAXA

Didn't want to say good-bye to Mount Fuji

Kuma is an employee of a logistics company in Yokohama. She works at the port. That's where the diamond princess is docked. Dahei Quay is Port of Yokohama's first man-made Island terminal with 25 large berths and the country's largest logistics centre. The adjacent Yokohama Bay Bridge is an important link to the Tokyo metropolitan area, where many private sector warehouses are located, and where many workers like Kuma work.

Every day at work, Kuma sees the infected, quarantined ship, not far from land but unable to dock. He was outraged to learn that it would be here for 14 days, and to see ambulance after ambulance carrying patients down from it. "NHK reports that the presence of the coronavirus will affect tourism, the economy and even the Olympics, " he said on twitter. "while the health of these ordinary workers working right by the port has not been noticed by anyone. ". "

The 22 year old Japanese girl, Nana, lives with her family near the port of Yokohama. She is studying at the Yokohama City University campus, just a few kilometers from the port. When the diamond princess docked in Port of Yokohama, students and residents around her panicked. In particular, after the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare announced on February 7th that 41 more people had been infected, the supply of face masks at nearby pharmacies was completely out of stock. "My friends are more worried about the quarantine than the pollen, " says Nana, whose mask barely covers the coming pollen season. It never occurred to her that the new coronavirus, a strange virus, could be so close to her. "instead of worrying about things getting worse, " he said, "figure out where to buy a mask. "

White-collar workers in downtown Yokohama, Hoshino told people that company colleagues occasionally discuss the quarantine of the ship news, but said they would not worry too much. The number of people wearing masks on the streets seems to be on the rise, but he went out of his way to say that it could not be determined because of the cruise ship. "after all, there are many Japanese who wear masks, and we are still some distance from Port of Yokohama. Most people don't believe the virus will spread here. "

The virus dropped like a bomb on the diamond princess. The impact rippled outward from the ship, layer by layer, weakening as the distance grew, but it did not subside.

A passenger traveling alone said on social media that he had reached his limit. She lived in a room with windows, but every morning she woke up and looked out through the windows, except for the water that separated the ship from the land, which was the quarantine officer in protective clothing, the self-defense force and the ambulance.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Ambulance on shore

The cruise ship radio said the parked ambulance did not mean anything, just to be prepared for any accidents. But that doesn't make it any easier. The number of passengers who tested positive for the new coronavirus is growing every day, and the numbers are getting creepier by the day. As of 12 February, a total of 492 persons had been quarantined on board, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 174, or 35 per cent of them. One of the infected persons was the quarantine officer who boarded the vessel to inspect the passengers. The quarantine officer, who boarded the ship on Feb. 3, wore a mask and gloves during his first two days of work, and did not wear protective clothing or goggles, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare said, he occasionally did not wear a mask -- a scenario that only added to the panic. On February 13, a woman and her child were confirmed infected. It is the first time a mother and child have been infected at the same time in Japan. The woman is 15 weeks pregnant, the first time a pregnant woman has been infected in Japan.

The number of confirmed cases on the diamond princess already exceeds the total number of confirmed cases in Japan and is increasing, making the situation increasingly difficult.

The new crown pneumonia epidemic continues, like the princess, no shore reliable, floating in the sea, there are many more cruise ships. The Hong Kong, China, cruise ship, the World Dream, was quarantined from shore for four days after carrying eight passengers who had been diagnosed with newly diagnosed pneumonia. Hong Kong announced on February 9 that the test results of the people on board were negative, it took more than 3,600 passengers and crew to disembark. The ship, carrying more than 2,200 people, was even more unfortunate. Although no one on board was confirmed to be infected with the virus, it was refused entry by several countries and regions on the grounds of epidemic prevention, and was sent to Japan, Taiwan, Guam, the Philippines and Thailand, he was at sea for two weeks before landing in Cambodia on February 13. Cruise ships have become a danger in this epidemic war that can not be ignored. Once an infected person is found, all are trapped in thousands of cubicles of a large confined space, with nowhere to go but in quarantine.

An Indian crew member of the Diamond Princess told Japanese media that no one could leave the ship at this time and that he did not know when he would be infected. Crew was his dream job, he says, and when it came true, it turned out to be a nightmare.

On February 11th, after the motion to "disembark asymptomatic passengers" was rejected, the Japanese government said it would start exploring a new solution: whether virus-susceptible people, such as the elderly and sick passengers, could be allowed to disembark earlier, quarantined in hospitals across Japan. Other doctors said the quarantine was wrong because there had been a mass infection, which would not have happened if passengers had been allowed to go home earlier, and that the quarantine had allowed the infection to spread.

Speaking at a press conference at noon on February 13, Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare Katsunobu Kato, the Secretary of State for the Civil Service, said patients and people over the age of 80 who had tested negative for new pneumonia could start disembarking tomorrow, February 14. If all goes well, the quarantine will end on the 19th, the cruise line said. The diamond princess is still unable to dock.

A female passenger from Japan, who had been on a cruise with friends, was on a ship during the quarantine, but could only communicate via the Internet. On social media, her name is "the imprisoned Princess, " and she says she likes to stand on the edge of the balcony, where she can see the warm rays of the setting sun against the snow on top of Mount Fuji, and you can see the traffic moving through the Yokohama Bay Bridge all the time. "This is a temporary separation from Mount Fuji, " she thought. But I don't want to say goodbye to Mount Fuji. "
